# Git Commands Guide

## clone

Copies a remote repository to your local computer.

### Syntax

```bash
git clone <repository-url>
```

### Example

```bash
git clone https://github.com/user/project.git
```

---

## checkout

Switches between branches or restores files.

### Syntax

```bash
git checkout <branch-name>
```

### Example

```bash
git checkout main
```

---

## -b

Used with `git checkout` to create a new branch and switch to it immediately.

### Syntax

```bash
git checkout -b <new-branch-name>
```

### Example

```bash
git checkout -b feature-login
```

---

## status

Shows the current state of the repository, including modified and untracked files.

### Syntax

```bash
git status
```

### Example

```bash
git status
```

---

## push

Uploads local commits to a remote repository.

### Syntax

```bash
git push
```

### Example

```bash
git push origin main
```

---

## -u

Sets the upstream branch when pushing.

### Syntax

```bash
git push -u origin main
```

### Example

```bash
git push -u origin feature-branch
```

---

## pull

Fetches and merges changes from a remote repository into the current branch.

### Syntax

```bash
git pull
```

### Example

```bash
git pull origin main
```

---

## add

Adds files to the staging area before committing.

### Syntax

```bash
git add <file-name>
```

### Example

```bash
git add README.md
```

To add all files:

```bash
git add .
```

---

## commit

Saves staged changes to the local repository.

### Syntax

```bash
git commit
```

### Example

```bash
git commit -m "Added new feature"
```

---

## -m

Adds a commit message directly from the command line.

### Syntax

```bash
git commit -m "message"
```

### Example

```bash
git commit -m "Fixed login bug"
```

---

## -a

Automatically stages tracked files before committing.

### Syntax

```bash
git commit -a
```

### Example

```bash
git commit -a -m "Updated documentation"
```

---

## -am

Combines the `-a` and `-m` flags to stage tracked files and add a commit message in one command.

### Syntax

```bash
git commit -am "message"
```

### Example

```bash
git commit -am "Refactored code"
```

---

## branch

Lists, creates, or deletes branches.

### Syntax

```bash
git branch
```

### Example

```bash
git branch
```

To create a branch:

```bash
git branch new-feature
```

---

## branch -a

Displays all local and remote branches.

### Syntax

```bash
git branch -a
```

### Example

```bash
git branch -a
```

---

## branch -d

Deletes a branch.

### Syntax

```bash
git branch -d <branch-name>
```

### Example

```bash
git branch -d old-feature
```

---

## merge

Combines changes from one branch into another.

### Syntax

```bash
git merge <branch-name>
```

### Example

```bash
git merge feature-login
```
